{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778377781192,"sessionID":"ses_1f06ce9c2ffeq0AGBe8JsXuCBd","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_v8OiiaMhIToHrvvzDXbjF8kr","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"WikipediaVersioned:","path":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/src/ontology","include":"uberon-edit.obo"},"output":"Found 40 matches\n/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo:\n  Line 41389: synonym: \"cholecyst\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Gallbladder&oldid=1092217922]\n\n  Line 50962: def: \"The visual area of the brain that is specialized for processing information about static and moving objects. The primary visual cortex, which is defined by its function or stage in the visual system, is approximately equivalent to the striate cortex, also known as Brodmann area 17, which is defined by its anatomical location.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Visual_cortex&oldid=1069729211]\n\n  Line 112463: synonym: \"anterior end of the temporal lobe\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Brodmann_area_38&oldid=984922149]\n\n  Line 112464: synonym: \"anterior temporal lobe\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Brodmann_area_38&oldid=984922149]\n\n  Line 112474: synonym: \"temporal pole\" RELATED [WikipediaVersioned:Brodmann_area_38&oldid=984922149]\n\n  Line 112476: synonym: \"temporopolar area 38 (H)\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Brodmann_area_38&oldid=984922149]\n\n  Line 220761: def: \"A foramen of the skull found at either posterior angle of the hard palate, for the transmission of the descending palatine vessels and greater palatine nerve.\" [FMA:53173, https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2825-0621, WikipediaVersioned:Greater_palatine_foramen&oldid=971687677]\n\n  Line 220769: def: \"A foramen of the skull found at either posterior angle of the hard palate behind the greater palatine foramen. One or more lesser palatine foramina perforate the pyramidal process of the palatine bone and carry the lesser palatine nerve.\" [FMA:53167, https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2825-0621, WikipediaVersioned:Lesser_palatine_foramina&oldid=870872639]\n\n  Line 221447: xref: WikipediaVersioned:Duodenojejunal_flexure&oldid=937307798\n\n  Line 221551: def: \"A fringe of tissue around the ostium of the fallopian tube, in the direction of the ovary.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Fallopian_tube&oldid=998395727]\n\n  Line 221625: def: \"A portal vein that drains the descending colon. It is a tributary of the inferior mesenteric vein, and follows the path of its corresponding artery, the left colic artery.\" [https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4183-8865, WikipediaVersioned:Left_colic_vein&oldid=964575339]\n\n  Line 221635: def: \"A portal vein that drains the ascending colon. It is a tributary of the superior mesenteric vein, and travels with its corresponding artery, the right colic artery.\" [https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4183-8865, WikipediaVersioned:Right_colic_vein&oldid=870898828]\n\n  Line 221666: def: \"The skin covering the inguinal region between the abdomen and the thigh on either side of the pubic bone.\" [http://orcid.org/0000-0001-7505-5418, PMID:32327715, PMID:468709, WikipediaVersioned:Groin&oldid=998393002]\n\n  Line 221786: def: \"The trabecular sinus is the lymph-filled space outside the trabeculae between lobules of the lymph node. This is a continuation of the subcapsular sinus which receives the afferent vessels and is present beneath the capsule. This space is traversed by both reticular fibers and cells in the lymph.\" [http://orcid.org/0000-0003-4183-8865, PMID:32491649, WikipediaVersioned:Lymph_node&oldid=1020495758]\n\n  Line 221796: def: \"A vein where lymph node venules condense and which exits at the lymph node hilum. It is also called hilar vein.\" [http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3440-1876, PMID:17067937, WikipediaVersioned:Lymph_node&oldid=1001655735#Structure]\n\n  Line 221806: def: \"An artery that enters the lymph node at the hilum and branches into smaller arterioles.\" [http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3440-1876, PMID:17067937, WikipediaVersioned:Lymph_node&oldid=1001655735#Structure]\n\n  Line 222161: def: \"A chest muscle with a role in forceful inspiration. In human, there are twelve levatores costarum on either side of the chest; they are small tendinous and fleshy bundles arising from the ends of the transverse processes of the seventh cervical and upper eleven thoracic vertebrae. They pass obliquely downward and laterally, like the fibers of the intercostales externi, and each is inserted into the outer surface of the rib immediately below the vertebra from which it takes origin, between the tubercle and the angle (levatores costarum breves). Each of the four lower muscles divides into two fasciculi, one of which is inserted as above described; the other passes down to the second rib below its origin (levatores costarum longi).\" [WikipediaVersioned:Levatores_costarum_muscles&oldid=876138804]\n\n  Line 222245: synonym: \"coccygeal gland\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Coccygeal_glomus&oldid=1019065130]\n\n  Line 222250: synonym: \"Luschka's gland\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Coccygeal_glomus&oldid=1019065130]\n\n  Line 222365: comment: In rats and mice, the anteroventral periventricular nucleus plus the periventricular nucleus make up the rostral periventricular region of the third ventricle (RP3V). Overlaps is used (instead of has_part that this comment suggests should be used) as PMID:17604108 suggest that the region refers to cells that are scattered in the area. {xref=\"WikipediaVersioned:Anteroventral_periventricular_nucleus&oldid=966137187\"}\n\n  Line 222477: def: \"A small cluster of neurons situated in the anterior hypothalamus, sitting just above and to the side of the optic chiasm in the brain of humans and other animals.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Ventrolateral_preoptic_nucleus&oldid=1045973404]\n\n  Line 222479: synonym: \"intermediate nucleus of the preoptic area (IPA)\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Ventrolateral_preoptic_nucleus&oldid=1045973404]\n\n  Line 222480: synonym: \"VLPO\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Ventrolateral_preoptic_nucleus&oldid=1045973404]\n\n  Line 222489: def: \"Collections of neurons in the central nervous system that have been demonstrated by histochemical fluorescence to contain the neurotransmitter norepinephrine (noradrenalin).\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_groups&oldid=965992184]\n\n  Line 222496: def: \"A group of cells in the vicinity of the lateral reticular nucleus of the medullary reticular formation that label for norepinephrine in primates.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_A1&oldid=903443213]\n\n  Line 222503: def: \"A group of cells in the vicinity of the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve in the medulla that label for norepinephrine in primates and rodents.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_A2&oldid=870891895]\n\n  Line 222510: def: \"A group of cells exhibiting noradrenergic fluorescence that, in the rat, are located in the Tegmen ventriculi quarti (roof of the fourth ventricle) ventral to the cerebellar nuclei, and in the macaque, are found at the edge of the lateral recess of the fourth ventricle caudally, extending to beneath the floor of the ventricle where they merge with the noradrenergic group A6, the locus ceruleus.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_A4&oldid=773500348]\n\n  Line 222519: def: \"A group of cells in the vicinity of the superior olivary complex in the pontine tegmentum that label for norepinephine in primates, rodents, and other mammals.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_A5&oldid=1081186383]\n\n  Line 222526: def: \"A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that is located in the pontine reticular formation ventral to the superior cerebellar peduncle of the pons in rodents and in primates.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_A7&oldid=870891935]\n\n  Line 222534: def: \"A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that are scattered in the nucleus subceruleus of the macaque.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_A6sc&oldid=773500411]\n\n  Line 222542: def: \"A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that are located in the central gray of the midbrain at the level of the trochlear nucleus in the squirrel monkey (Saimiri) and to a lesser degree in the macaque.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Noradrenergic_cell_group_Acg&oldid=981960786]\n\n  Line 222586: def: \"A group of neurons in the floor of the fourth ventricle, in close proximity to the nucleus of the hypoglossal nerve in the gray substance of the medulla oblongata, all of which contain cells with characteristics suggestive of reticular connections.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Perihypoglossal_nuclei&oldid=821664008]\n\n  Line 222587: synonym: \"nuclei perihypoglossales\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Perihypoglossal_nuclei&oldid=821664008]\n\n  Line 222588: synonym: \"perihypoglossal complex\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Perihypoglossal_nuclei&oldid=821664008]\n\n  Line 222589: synonym: \"perihypoglossal nuclear complex\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Perihypoglossal_nuclei&oldid=821664008]\n\n  Line 222591: synonym: \"satellite nuclei\" EXACT [WikipediaVersioned:Perihypoglossal_nuclei&oldid=821664008]\n\n  Line 222599: def: \"Nerve fibers that originate in the magnocellular red nucleus, cross to the other side of the midbrain, and descend in the lateral part of the brainstem tegmentum in the midbrain, and travel through the lateral funiculus of the spinal cord, coursing adjacent to the lateral corticospinal tract.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Rubrospinal_tract&oldid=1002226835]\n\n  Line 222682: def: \"A small cluster of neurons dorsal to the facial motor nucleus in the pontine tegmentum.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Accessory_facial_motor_nucleus&oldid=1046234765]\n\n  Line 223062: def: \"The part of the cerebral cortex that is responsible for the perception of taste.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Gustatory_cortex&oldid=1048584788]\n\n  Line 223401: def: \"The region where the frontal, parietal, temporal, and sphenoid bones fuse.\" [WikipediaVersioned:Temple_(anatomy)&oldid=1104547137]\n","metadata":{"matches":40,"truncated":false},"title":"WikipediaVersioned:","time":{"start":1778377781141,"end":1778377781179}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0590ff560823f7410169ffe4350ce4819dada40ccb305acc2e"}},"id":"prt_e0f936f59001w2dv3w7plJWcIc","sessionID":"ses_1f06ce9c2ffeq0AGBe8JsXuCBd","messageID":"msg_e0f935cd8001c7fZaZ1Ixm2O4c"}}
